member.name: T:Ansys.Mechanical.DataModel.ConstructionLines.Utility.RollmarkAutomation
member.summary: This class is designed to be used to automate the creation of rollmarks for the engine. When used with a `using` statement, a rollmark may be created after the scope is exited. A rollmark is only created, however, if a call to `MarkCleanOperation()` has been made on the instance. Otherwise, the operation is treated as a failure and no rollmark will be attempted. This class cooperates with the `IAnsTransactionOperationTracker` from a DSConstructionLine instance to coordinate the generation of a single rollmark for an entire transaction. If no transaction has been started, it is expected that a rollmark will be created upon a clean call to `endOperation()`.

member.summary: Creates a new tag with the given name

member.name: M:Ansys.Mechanical.Application.ObjectTag.attach(Ansys.ACT.Automation.Mechanical.Project)
member.summary: This attach method makes sure the tag is currently in a valid state to attach itself to the UI. Then it record the project given, and transfers itself into an AttachedObjectTag. It does this by taking each object in the detached tag's local list of objects and adding them to the attached tag.
member.remarks: An object tag is in one of two states, attached or detached to the UI and the internal IDSObjectTags objects. If a tag is attached, then every DataModelObject in the Tree that has that tag will reflect it in that specific object's IDSObjectTags. If that object is detached, then no object's IDSObjectTags in the tree will have this tag. Instead, the tag itself will keep track of which objects are a part of the tag with a local list. When a detached tag gets added to the DataModel, it gets attached, iterating through each objects in the tag's local object list, and adding the tag to each DataModelObject's IDSObjectTags.
member.param: The current Data Model's project

member.name: M:Ansys.Mechanical.Application.ObjectTag.detach
member.summary: The detach method first makes sure the tag is in a valid state to become detached, then transforms its internal object _tags into a DetachedTag object, transfering its contents.
member.remarks: For explanation of what being attached/detached means, look at the remarks tag for the attach method.

member.summary: Makes sure one of this bolt pretension's fields is ready to use. This method should be called before the first read or write operation on any of the fields of this load. Using the GUI, it appears that Mechanical does not initialize the load until it is changed for the first time. Its input values are not consistent with the steps defined in the analysis settings (neither in count nor in value). Using the load in the uninitialized state leads to strange behaviour and wrong values.
member.param: Field whose inputs should be checked.

member.summary: Allows you to specify the height for the volume of solid elements in the method of Extrude.

member.name: P:Ansys.ACT.Automation.Mechanical.MeshExtrude.RevolutionAngle
member.summary: Allows you to specify angle of revolution for the solid elements in the method of Revolve.

member.summary: Allows you to specify the thickness for surface coating. The Thickness option is available only when the Stiffness Behavior is set to Membrane Only or Membrane and Bending.

member.name: P:Ansys.ACT.Automation.Mechanical.MeshExtrude.AxisOfRevolution
member.summary: Allows you to select the coordinate axis along which the selected elements can be revolved. The available options are X Axis, Y Axis, Z Axis.

member.name: P:Ansys.ACT.Automation.Mechanical.MeshExtrude.ExtrudeBy
member.summary: Allows you to specify the method of Extrude. The available options are Use Coordinate System and Face Normal.

member.name: P:Ansys.ACT.Automation.Mechanical.MeshExtrude.UseCoordinateSystem
member.summary: The Use Coordinate System allows you to select any of the XYZ coordinate axis in the method of Extrude.

member.name: P:Ansys.ACT.Automation.Mechanical.MeshExtrude.Method
member.summary: Allows you to select the method of Pull. There are three methods. They are Extrude, Revolve and Surface Coating.

member.name: P:Ansys.ACT.Automation.Mechanical.MeshExtrude.StiffnessOption
member.summary: Allows you to provide the stiffness option of the shell body created by surface coating. The available options are Stress Evaluation Only, Membrane Only, Membrane and Bending.

member.name: P:Ansys.ACT.Automation.Mechanical.MeshExtrude.UpTo
member.summary: Allows you to generate elements up to the specified target. The target can be faces from solids or sheet bodies and multiple faces with sharing topoedge.

member.name: P:Ansys.ACT.Automation.Mechanical.MeshExtrude.MergeNodes

member.name: P:Ansys.ACT.Automation.Mechanical.MeshExtrude.MergeProfileNodes
member.summary: Allows you to merge nodes on the profile body and pull generated body.

member.name: P:Ansys.ACT.Automation.Mechanical.MeshExtrude.Suppressed
member.summary: Allows you to suppress the selected entities. You can select Yes to suppress the selected entities and No to unsuppress the selected entities. The default value is No.

member.summary: The target can be faces from solids or sheet bodies and multiple faces with sharing topoedge in Extrude UpTo.

member.remarks: This method should be called before adding/removing objects to prevent multiple redraws. It should be used in association with a using/with block to ensure the Resume controller method to be called. Indeed, the Dispose method of controller automatically calls the Resume method.

with(ExtAPI.DataModel.Tree.Suspend()): for i in range(10): ExtAPI.DataModel.Project.Model.AddComment()

member.name: T:Ansys.ACT.Common.Post.ResultRepository
member.summary: Represents the result repository. It is aimed at being the main entry point for the core application to get result readers from result files, hiding the burden of the management of those readers (instanciation, caching and disposal) from the client code. For each result file, the reader code that actually deals with reading the file is hosted in a standalone process. Reusing the same reader as the one that Mechanical uses would lead to unpredictable failures because ACT would step on Mechanical toes.

member.summary: Changes the definition type for a field of the wrapped object from Mechanical.
member.remarks: The contract is the adapter is expected to raise a if the given definition type for its component is illegal. Mechanical does not support all definition types for all its field provider objects through its User Interface. member.summary: Tries to set the discrete values for an output variable of the managed field.
member.remarks: This method should be useless in most cases since the general behaviour implemented by the variable - which consists in modifying the underlying load variation - should suffice. member.name: P:Ansys.ACT.Mechanical.Fields.VariableSignature.IntuitiveIndex
member.summary: Gets an index that reflects the position of the variable within its container load variation any Mechanical user would intuitively think of by looking at the GUI. For instance, the first variable in the "Independents" collection of a ILoadVariation object from Mechanical is wrapped by a signature that uses =0 since this is the actual position in the Independents collection. But for the user, this variable is the second independent variable, the first being the one returned by the "PrimaryIndependent" property of ILoadVariation. In this example, IntuitiveIndex would then return 1.
member.remarks: This index makes sense when speaking about a ILoadVariation but since this API wraps load variations in a more convenient manner, this property is not worth being exposed to the end-user. Indeed, it is not well suitable to output variables because whereas there can be several "Dependent" variables in a ILoadVariation object, there is always a single output per object, to remain consistent over the various types of load variations that can be encoutered in Mechanical (some use several outputs gathered in the same load variation while some other would use several load variations with a single output each). That is why even if it is more "intuitive" than can be, this index is still a bit too complex to grasp for the end-user.

member.summary: This method uses CreateRawTripleQuotedString and FormatOddNumberBackSlashesInRawString to prepare the right hand side of a string for journaling. It is currently used by CommandsController.
member.param: Original text.
member.returns: String that can be used in a python command for journaling.

member.name: M:Ansys.ACT.Mechanical.StringManipulationHelper.FormatDoubleQuotesInAStringForJournaling(System.String)
member.summary:
This method formats given string x in a way that any double quotes inside the string are not treated as raw string. We need this method to be used by the controller for Commands object, because we pass in the API command to be journaled to the commands layer using triple quotes and raw string identifier. In that case we don't want any triple quotes typed by the user to be treated as a raw string.
Ei. User types in "something is """ something", let this string be str, the commands controller receives "something is \"\"\" something" from the client. If we use this string as it is, in preparing the command to be journaled. We would write something like "cmd.Input = r\"\"\"something is \"\"\" something\"\"\"", in this case the triple quotes in str will not work because the command string that needs to be journaled wouldn't know which triple quotes are pairs, and we also don't want to treat the triple quotes as a raw string otherwise when the user uses the journaled command they would end up with backslashes in their text where there should not be.
In this case, we would want our command string to look something like this. "cmd.Input = r\"\"\"something is \"\"\" + "\"\"\"" + r\"\"\"" + something \"\"\"" Given the text = "something is \"\"\" something", this method will return - ["r\"\"\"something is \"\"\"", "\"\\\"\\\"\\\"\"", "r\"\"\" something\"\"\"] As it can been seen above the string is now split into multiple raw strings, and excludes the double quotes that the user typed.

member.name: M:Ansys.ACT.Mechanical.StringManipulationHelper.FormatOddNumberBackSlashesInRawString(System.Collections.Generic.List{System.String})
member.summary: This method simply extracts the last backslash into it's own string in a raw triple quoted string that ends with with odd number of backslashes. ei. r""" some string \\\""", this would not work because the last backslash is treated as an escape char for the first double quote. This method will turn the above string into r""" some string \\""" + "\\", which now has the same effect that was intended by original string but is correct in the python syntax.
member.param: List of raw triple quoted string generated using CreateRawTripleQuotedString
member.returns: List of strings where no raw triple quoted string ends with odd number of back slashes.

member.name: T:Ansys.ACT.WorkBench.Properties.ContractAnnotationAttribute
member.summary: Describes dependency between method input and output.
member.syntax:
Function Definition Table syntax:
FDT ::= FDTRow [;FDTRow]*
FDTRow ::= Input => Output | Output <= Input
Input ::= ParameterName: Value [, Input]*
Output ::= [ParameterName: Value]* {halt|stop|void|nothing|Value}
Value ::= true | false | null | notnull | canbenull
If method has single input parameter, it's name could be omitted.
Using halt (or void/nothing, which is the same) for method output means that the methos doesn't return normally.
canbenull annotation is only applicable for output parameters.
You can use multiple [ContractAnnotation] for each FDT row, or use single attribute with rows separated by semicolon.

item.code: [ContractAnnotation("halt <= condition: false")] public void Assert(bool condition, string text) // Regular Assertion method
[ContractAnnotation("s:null => true")] public bool IsNullOrEmpty(string s) // String.IsNullOrEmpty
[ContractAnnotation("s:null=>false; =>true,result:notnull; =>false, result:null")] public bool TryParse(string s, out Person result)
